Yes
If you write code like this
```
static class Test
{
    private static byte[] data = new byte[] { 0x0 };
}
```
After compiling its actual code is
```
static class Test
{
    private static byte[] data;

    private static void .cctor()
    {
        data = new byte[] { 0x0 };
    }
}
```
So you need to view the .cctor code of the static class to get its initialization value

